<%= faq_schema([
  { question: "What is CSS Flexbox?", answer: "CSS Flexible Box Layout (Flexbox) is a one-dimensional layout model that distributes space among items in a container and aligns them along a single axis. Unlike older layout methods like floats and inline-block, Flexbox makes it straightforward to center elements, distribute space evenly, and handle dynamic or unknown sizes. It works along either a row (horizontal) or column (vertical) main axis." },
  { question: "What is the difference between justify-content and align-items?", answer: "justify-content controls how items are distributed along the main axis (horizontal for row direction, vertical for column). align-items controls how items are positioned along the cross axis (vertical for row, horizontal for column). Think of justify-content as controlling left-right spacing and align-items as controlling top-bottom alignment, when flex-direction is set to row." },
  { question: "When should I use Flexbox vs CSS Grid?", answer: "Use Flexbox for one-dimensional layouts where items flow in a single row or column, such as navigation bars, button groups, card rows, or centering content. Use CSS Grid for two-dimensional layouts where you need to control both rows and columns simultaneously, such as page layouts, image galleries, or dashboard layouts. Many modern designs combine both: Grid for the overall page structure and Flexbox for component-level alignment." },
  { question: "What does flex-wrap do?", answer: "By default, flex items try to fit on one line (nowrap). Setting flex-wrap to 'wrap' allows items to flow onto multiple lines when they exceed the container width. 'wrap-reverse' does the same but starts new lines above instead of below (for row direction). This is essential for responsive layouts where items should stack on smaller screens." },
  { question: "How does the gap property work with Flexbox?", answer: "The gap property adds consistent spacing between flex items without affecting the outer edges of the container. Before gap was supported in Flexbox, developers used margins and negative margins to achieve similar results. Gap accepts one value for both row and column gaps, or two values for separate row and column gaps. It is now supported in all modern browsers." }
]) %>

